An Evening with Composer, Lyricist Stephen Sondheim and NYT's Frank Rich in a Discussion of the American Musical Theater









Media contact: Noelle Lemoine, communications assistant; tele: (413) 597-4277; email: [email protected]
WILLIAMSTOWN, Mass., January 12, 2010 — On Saturday, Jan. 23, Williams College welcomes back composer and lyricist Stephen Sondheim, who graduated in 1950. He will be joined on stage by author and New York Times columnist and former chief theatre critic Frank Rich in a conversation about Sondheim’s career, including his collaborations with Leonard Bernstein, Jerome Robbins, and Tim Burton; the state of the American musical theater; and Sondheim’s creative process, specifically works ranging from his early shows “Gypsy” and “West Side Story” to such later classics as “Company,” “Follies,” and “Sweeney Todd.”
Stephen SondheimSondheim has not only collaborated on more than a dozen landmark shows and written countless standard songs, but is acknowledged as the single most influential force in “bringing the Broadway musical into the modern age.” Rich has called Sondheim “the greatest and perhaps best-known artist in the American musical stage” (Vanity Fair 3/08).
The evening’s unscripted conversation promises to provide a personal view of Sondheim and his life in the theater. The event will take place at 8 p.m. in Chapin Hall on the Williams campus. It is open to the public, free of charge, but tickets are required. Tickets may be reserved online (limit two/person) at https://webapps.williams.edu/admin-forms/ephpubevent/ or by phone (413) 597-4435.
While still in his 20s, Sondheim contributed the lyrics to Arthur Laurents’ and Jerome Robbins’ “West Side Story” (music by Leonard Bernstein) and “Gypsy” (music by Jule Styne). His first produced Broadway show as both composer and lyricist was “A Funny Thing Happened On the Way to the Forum” (1962). Sondheim went on to create a remarkable succession of groundbreaking musicals, including “Company” (1970), “Follies” (1971), “A Little Night Music” (1973), “Sweeney Todd” (1979), and “Sunday in the Park with George” (1984).
It is hard to find a musical today that hasn’t been influenced by Sondheim’s remaking the rules that once governed the traditional Broadway musical.
Sondheim has won every coveted award: the Kennedy Center honors, Pulitzer Prize, multiple Grammys, an Academy Award, and multiple Tonys (more than any other composer) including a special award for Lifetime Achievement in the Theater in 2008. He was elected to the American Academy of Arts and Letters, the most prestigious academic society in America, in 1983.
Rich is an op-ed columnist for The New York Times, who has been said to “view political life through a theatrical lens” (NYTs 4/07). He served as the Time’s chief drama critic, beginning in 1980, the year he joined the Times, for 14 years. Leaving the dramatic hot seat, from 2003 to 2005, he was the Times front-page columnist for the Sunday Arts & Leisure section. Before joining the Times, he was a founding editor of The Richmond Mercury and a film and television critic at Time Magazine.
His opinion matters: he is a recipient of the prestigious George Polk Award for commentary, given annually by Long Island University in honor of contributions to journalistic integrity and investigative reporting.
Rich is the author of “The Greatest Story Ever Sold: The Decline and Fall of Truth from 9/11 to Katrina” and “Hot Seat: Theater Criticism for The New York Times, 1980-1993,” among other titles.
He graduated from Harvard College in 1971, where he was editorial chairman of the Harvard Crimson. While at the Crimson, Rich wrote a lengthy essay about the Sondheim musical “Follies'” pre-Broadway run in Boston. It is reported the article “fascinated” director Harold Prince and “absolutely” intrigued Sondheim, who invited the undergraduate to lunch to discuss the production.
The evening’s event at Williams College is sponsored by the President’s Office, the Leadership Studies Program, the Program in Jewish Studies, and the music and theatre departments.
END
Founded in 1793, Williams College is the second oldest institution of higher learning in Massachusetts. The college’s 2,000 students are taught by a faculty noted for the quality of their teaching and research, and the achievement of academic goals includes active participation of students with faculty in their research. Students’ educational experience is enriched by the residential campus environment in Williamstown, Mass., which provides a host of opportunities for interaction with one another and with faculty beyond the classroom. Admission decisions are made regardless of a student’s financial ability, and the college provides grants and other assistance to meet the demonstrated needs of all who are admitted.
To visit the college on the Internet: http://www.williams.edu/ Williams College can also be found on Facebook: http://www.facebook.com/williamscollege and Twitter: http://twitter.com/williamscollege

END











